# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: american-society-of-civil-engineers
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] The **reconstruction of New Orleans** refers to the process of rebuilding the city following the failure of levees and floodwalls during Hurricane Katrina on August 29, 2005.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] The federally built hurricane protection, called the Lake Pontchartrain and Vicinity Hurricane Protection Project failed, resulting in breaches that released tens of billions of gallons of water flooding approximately 80% of the city.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] The flooding remained in the city for days, in many places for weeks.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] Over 204,000 homes were severely damaged or destroyed, and an estimated 200,000 vehicles were totaled.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] More than 800,000 citizens were displaced—the greatest displacement in the United States since the Dust Bowl of the 1930s.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] Residential reconstruction was hindered by bureaucratic problems in the heavily criticized Road Home rebuilding program which was federally funded and state-managed.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] Critics also said that national politics factored into the program which was based on pre-storm home values, leading to disparities between rich and poor.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] Faith-based and volunteer agencies provided considerable supplemental relief.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] The original flood protection system was redesigned and built at a cost of $14.5 billion and was 100% funded by the Army Corps through post-Katrina emergency appropriations.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] The new system was renamed the Hurricane & Storm Damage Risk Reduction System (HSDRRS) and is an integrated flood protection system designed to provide the Greater New Orleans area with a 100-year level of risk reduction.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] Flooding due to rain and storms has long been an issue since the New Orleans's early settlement due to the city's location on a delta marsh, 50% of which sits below sea level.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] The city is surrounded by the Mississippi River to the south, Lake Pontchartrain to the north, and Lake Borgne to the east.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] Construction of the levees along the River began soon after the city was founded, and more extensive river levees were built as the city grew.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] The levees were originally designed to prevent damage caused by seasonal flooding.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] By summer of 2005, the 17th Street Canal and London Avenue Canal are used for drainage, to pump water from the city streets out to Lake Pontchartrain.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] Floodwalls (called I-walls) embedded in the canals are one foot (300 mm) wide at the top and widened to two feet (610 mm) at the base.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] The visible portion is a concrete cap on steel sheet pile that anchors to the wall.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] Sheet piles are interlocked steel columns, in this case at least 30 feet (9.1 m) long, with 6 to 10 feet (1.8 to 3.0 m) visible above ground.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] The wide, navigable Industrial Canal is used for shipping.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] Prior to 1965, the local Orleans Levee District (OLD) built and maintained New Orleans' drainage and hurricane protection and shouldered 100% of the cost.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] But, heavy flooding during Hurricane Betsy brought concerns regarding flooding from hurricanes to the forefront.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] In the Flood Control Act of 1965, Congress directed the Army Corps have sole authority over the design and construction of the New Orleans area flood protection and the OLD shall maintain projects when completed and pay 30% of the cost.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] The flood protection project was called the Lake Pontchartrain and Vicinity Hurricane Protection Project.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] Forty years later when Katrina struck, the flood protection was between 60-90% completed with an estimated completion date of 2015, despite the initial expectation of completion within thirteen years.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] As of May 2005, work in Orleans Parish was certified as 90% complete, with "some work remaining" along the London Avenue Canals, and 70% complete in Jefferson Parish.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] There were many predictions of hurricane risk in New Orleans before Hurricane Katrina in August, 2005.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] In 2001, the *Houston Chronicle* published a story which predicted that a severe hurricane striking New Orleans, "would strand 250,000 people or more, and probably kill one of 10 left behind as the city drowned under 20 feet (6.1 m) of water.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] Thousands of refugees could land in Houston." Many concerns also focused around the fact that the city's levee system was only designed for hurricanes of no greater intensity than category 3.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] In addition, the region's natural defenses, the surrounding marshland and the barrier islands, have been dwindling in recent years due to human interference, mainly the energy industry.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] On Saturday, August 27, while Katrina was a Category 3 storm gathering strength in the Gulf of Mexico, the Army Corps of Engineers Mississippi Valley Division was preparing and posturing elements from as far as Hawaii.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] Anticipating the possibility of a Category 5 storm placing water in New Orleans, preparations began for drainage operations.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] On August 29, 2005, as Katrina made its second and third landfalls on the Louisiana-Mississippi coast, Corps District Commander, Col.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] Richard Wagenaar, and a team worked out of an emergency operations shelter in New Orleans.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] Other teams waited in the storm's path across the Gulf coast.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] Coast Guard, Army National Guard and other state and federal authorities to bring in all assets available to expedite the process.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] There were 28 reported failures in the first 24 hours and over 50 were reported in the ensuing days.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] Before dawn on Monday August 29, 2005, waves overtopped and eroded the Mississippi River-Gulf Outlet levees.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] CDT, levees along the Gulf Intracoastal Waterway, lining the south side of New Orleans East, also overtopped and breached.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] The surge flooded the primarily middle to upper class Black region.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] On the west edge of New Orleans, between 6 and 7:00 am, a monolith on the east side of the London Avenue Canal failed and allowed water over 10 feet deep into Fillmore Gardens, a mostly Black middle class neighborhood.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] At about 6:30 a.m., on the western edge of the city, several monoliths failed on the 17th Street Canal.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] A torrent of water blasted into Lakeview, a mainly White middle class neighborhood of homeowners.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] Local fire officials reported the breach.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] At about 8am, a second breach opened up in the London Avenue Canal, this one on the opposite side allowing water to flood the Lake Vista neighborhood.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] The Duncan and Bonnabel Pumping Stations were also reported to have suffered roof damage, and were non-functional.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] CDT, a much larger second hole opened up in the Industrial Canal just south of the initial breach.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] Floodwaters from the two breaches combined to submerge the entire historic Lower Ninth Ward in over 10 feet of water.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] Between 7 and 8:00 am, the west side of the London Avenue Canal breached, in addition to the east side, and flooded the adjacent mixed-race neighborhood of homeowners.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] In September 2022, the Associated Press issued a style guide change to Katrina stating that reporters when writing about the storm in New Orleans should note that “…levee failures played a major role in the devastation in New Orleans.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] Army Corps' engineers initially believed that water in the 17th Street Canal overtopped the floodwall, scoured behind the wall, and caused it to collapse.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] However, three local fire captains confirmed with video footage that the floodwall had failed before water reached the top.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] The floodwall breached on the lower (New Orleans West End) side inland from the Old Hammond Highway Bridge.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] There were three major breaches at the Industrial Canal; one on the upper side near the junction with MR-GO, and two on the lower side along the Lower Ninth Ward, between Florida Avenue and Claiborne Avenue.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] The London Avenue Canal breached in two places, on the upper side just back from Robert E.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] Lee Boulevard, and on the lower side a block in from the Mirabeau Avenue Bridge.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] By the evening of August 29, 2005, approximately 28 levee failures were reported throughout the city.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] Approximately 66% to 75% of the city was now under water.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] The National Weather Service had predicted intense wind damage severity, but these predictions were not realized due to Katrina's path.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] Nonetheless, many power lines were down and the remains of trees and buildings blocked streets.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] As Army Corps workers began working with the Federal Emergency Management Agency (FEMA) begin work on city cleanup and civil engineering tasks, several boats surveyed the flooded areas and blocked waterways around the city.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] The Army Corps used crane barges to remove barges that had been washed atop bridges and other structures.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] Plans were made to begin levee work, including the placement of 3,000 pound sand bags on the 17 Street Canal.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] Army National Guard helicopters began assisting in this operation August 31.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] Meanwhile, Lake Pontchartrain started slowly draining and was expected to return to normal levels in about 36 hours.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] Approximately 45 bridges were damaged by some aspect of the hurricane.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] Several major bridges were among the worst damaged, with the I-10 Twin Span Bridge as the most catastrophic failure with over 470 spans separated from their supports and nearly 65 fallen completely into the water.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] Other vital bridges damaged enough to impede traffic included the Pontchartrain Causeway, St.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] Louis Bay Bridge, and Biloxi Bay Bridge.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] Mississippi railways and roads, when not affected by bridge collapsing, were disrupted due to heavy debris.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] Removal costs are estimated at $200 million for that area.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] Damage to the Louisiana roadway systems was mostly due to washouts and has been deemed minimal.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] There were seven major Investigations of levee failures during Hurricane Katrina.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] The first investigation was announced on October 19, 2005.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] Defense Secretary Donald Rumsfeld announced that an independent panel of experts, under the direction of the National Academy of Sciences, would convene to evaluate the performance of the New Orleans levee system and issue a final report in eight months.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] The panel would study the results provided by the two existing teams of experts that had already examined the levee failures.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] The academy concluded that "the engineering of the levee system was not adequate.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] The procedures for designing and constructing hurricane protection systems will have to be improved, and the designing organizations must upgrade their engineering capabilities.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] The levees must be seen not as a system to protect real estate but as a set of dams to protect people.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] The recovery of New Orleans was seen as a three-phase process: first and most immediate, to unwater the city and assess flood protection.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] Second, to provide an interim level of protection to get the city through the 2005 hurricane season and later high water, and over the long-term, to return the flood protection system to pre-hurricane conditions.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] This would take a tremendous amount of study, research, funding and construction.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] Robert Crear stated on September 2 that the process of removing water was estimated to take between 36 and 80 days.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] The Army Corps performed a detailed assessment of about 350 miles (560 km) of hurricane levee and developed a comprehensive, prioritized plan to repair it and the pumping stations that support New Orleans and surrounding areas.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] "The system in its present condition does not ensure that the city will be protected from flooding resulting from storms or hurricanes," stressed Col.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] Duane Gapinski, Task Force Unwatering commander.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] State and local leaders were informed as assessments were being completed and repairs were made.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] Eight Honolulu Army engineers left on August 28 help with relief efforts and to worked with the 249th Engineer Battalion (Prime Power) to assess, install and maintain emergency generators.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] By September 6, the pump stations were pumping water from the flooded city back into Lake Ponchartrain.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] Portable pumps were used to remove water from the city.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] By September 6, the estimated area of flooding was reduced to 60%.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] On September 7th, 23 of the 148 permanent pumps had now been restored to operation.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] On September 7, it was estimated, based on average seasonal rainfall, that Orleans Parish would be drained by the week of October 2, 2005.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] New Orleans East would be drained by the week of October 8, 2005, and Plaquemines Parish would be drained by the week of October 18, 2005.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] By Saturday, September 10, 2005, there were 148 organic pumps in the New Orleans area being worked, with an average of 26 permanent pumps operating, pumping 9,125 cubic feet per second (cfs) and 39 portable pumps were operating, pumping 723 cfs.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] As of midnight Sept 11, three-quarters of a billion gallons of water was being drained - or the equivalent to an Olympic-sized swimming pool was being drained every two seconds.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] By September 15, 2005, the inundation of the city had been reduced from 80% to 40%, although flooded areas were not expected to be habitable for a long while.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] On September 18, the Army Corps estimated the New Orleans area was more than 80 percent unwatered.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] Corps officials estimated the overall unwatering effort, given normal seasonal rainfall, would be completed no later than early October, 2005.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] The Army Corps created Task Force Guardian to provide an interim level of protection to get the city through the 2005 hurricane season and in the longer term restore the city's ability to resist a Category 3 hurricane by June of 2006.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] Task Force Guardian identified the most critical drainage canal breach sites that needed immediate closing.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] These were the London Avenue Canal in the Gentilly region of the city and also the 17th Street Canal in the western most part of the city.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] The breach at the 17th Street Canal, a levee-floodwall combination, was found to be about 450 (137 m) long.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] Operating with pump station 6, the canal is a critical element of the New Orleans main basin flood control as a drainage conduit.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] The Corps released two contracts to close the breach in the 17th Street Canal.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] A Texas National Guard helicopter dropped 3,000 pound sandbags into the breach site and then switched to 6,000 pound sandbags.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] These were completely washed away and the initial attempt failed.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] The Corps then contracted to build an access roads to the breach site from Old Hammond Highway and fill in the breach with rock, stone and crushed concrete hauled in by truck.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] Rock was being transported from offsite to complete the access road and closure at the 17th Street breach.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] The next step at the 17th Street Canal was to cut off flow from Lake Pontchartrain.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] Corps officials then worked with Orleans Parish and Louisiana Department of Transportation officials and Boh Bros.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] Construction Co., to drive 150 feet of sheet pilings at the lakefront.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] By September 1, 2005, the mouth of the 17th Street Canal had been sealed with the sheet piling preventing lake water from getting to the levee breach.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] On September 7th, three pumps were operating and discharging water at around 2,250 cubic feet per second, or cfs.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] One week to the day after Katrina, the 17th Street Canal breach was closed.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] The London Avenue Canal had breach sites on both sides approximately ten city blocks apart.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] Texas Army National Guard Chinook and Blackhawk helicopter crews had placed an average of 600 7,000-pound sandbags each day into the breaches.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] Depending on the helicopters lift capability, Corps riggers averaged one to three hookups every two minutes during daylight hours.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] Sandbagging operations ran 24 hours for ten days.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] As at the 17th Street Canal, water flow from Lake Pontchartrain into the canal had been cut off when Army Corps contractors drove 150 feet (46 m) of steel piling across the canal mouth to seal it.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] From the London Avenue west side breach, a road was built to the second breach area at Mirabeau Avenue.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] Corps personnel were monitoring both breach sites around the clock.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] Contractors maintained cranes at the sites to regulate flow levels by adjusting sheet pile walls at the mouths of the canals into Lake Pontchartrain.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] By September 5, 2005, the breaches of London Avenue Canal were closed.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] By September 12, 2005, water had overtopped the temporary breach closure at the London Avenue Canal because of operations at Pump Station 3.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] This caused the canal to rise faster than the temporary pumps at the end of the canal could drain.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] Operations at Pump Station 3 were immediately stopped and a few sheet piles were removed to allow the canal water level to equalize.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] Construction of an access road to the second London Avenue Canal breach just north of the Mirabeau bridge was completed September 14.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] Engineers found two breaches on the east side of the Inner Harbor Navigational Canal and one on its west side.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] They closed the larger of the two breaches on the east side yesterday and filled the smaller of the two breaches with clay and stone.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] Work will begin on the west side as soon as feasible.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] Pump Station 19 on the west side of the Industrial Canal had been running for some time.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] On September 7th, pump station 19 just north of Florida Avenue, was 1,300 cpf.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] On the Industrial Canal, Army Corps contractors used crane barges to remove two barges from “atop” the Florida Avenue Bridge, also commonly known as the L&N Bridge.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] Work continued on nearby waterways, including several locks which were closed.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] Use of some of the locks required raising bridges.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] The Industrial Canal Lock needed repair, and its lockmaster raised the St.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] Claude Avenue bridge, but lowered it because of hostility from civilians wanting to cross on both sides.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] Steps in repairing the Industrial canal breach include removal of two damaged barges and one that had sunk.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] The entire floodwall between the two bridges (Claiborne to the south and Florida Avenue to the north) was replaced with a T-wall and completed in mid-June 2006.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] The first new homes after Katrina in the Lower Ninth Ward were completed in 2007.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] Katrina's surge and waves had a devastating effect on the levees along the GIWW that was constructed with materials dredged from the adjacent channels using hydraulic fill.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] The back sides of the levees, especially where they were composed of erodible materials, was scoured away, leading to complete breaching in many cases.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] One week after Katrina, Pump Station 10 at the lakefront of New Orleans East was actually pumping.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] Four more portable pumps were to be added in support of Pump Station 15 to increase the overall capacity.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] Army Corps of Engineers workers were in New Orleans.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] Over 500 contracted workers were involved in repairs.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] Of the 174 pumps now in New Orleans area, 37 were operational, most of them operating at one-eighth capacity.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] On September 9, state and federal officials stated that the water that flooded much of New Orleans could be pumped out faster than expected.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] By September 13, most of the Ninth Ward and the southern part of Orleans Parish were dry enough for normal recovery operations to begin.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] Water remained in the northern part of the parish and would be pumped out using Pump Stations 12 and 4, and reinforced with about a dozen temporary pumps.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] The Coast Guard opened the Mississippi River to surface traffic within 5 days of Hurricane Katrina’s landfall.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] All of the aids to navigation that were destroyed were rebuilt or replaced within six weeks.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] The focus of pump repair efforts shifted from Pump Station 1 to Pump Station 4 in Orleans Parish.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] On September 15, 7.5 billion US gallons (28,000,000 m3) of water was pumped out of the city.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] On Monday, September 5, 2005, electrical power began to be restored to buildings in the central business district of New Orleans on a priority basis.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] By Thursday, September 8, Entergy had restored 9 of 17 electricity generating units in the New Orleans area to service.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] Entergy's 1000 MW Waterford and Watson plants were still out of service, with the Watson plant expected to require 6–12 weeks to repair.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] By Friday, electrical power had been restored to 11% of New Orleans customers.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] Also, officials were organizing to have work begin as soon as Monday, September 12, to rebuild the, "twin spans" I-10 bridge to New Orleans.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] On Tuesday, September 6, 2005, the Port of New Orleans, the largest U.S. port in terms of tonnage handled, was able to receive and service relief ships.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] It was estimated that resumption of commercial shipments would take at least 14 days.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] By Wednesday, September 7, 2005, safe drinking water was available in some West Bank areas, including Algiers and the Jefferson Parish suburbs, and some water pressure was available in New Orleans for fire fighting.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] All sewage from the city was flowing untreated into the Mississippi.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] The Lower Mississippi River was open during daylight hours to shallow draft traffic and deep draft vessels less than 39 feet (12 m).
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] A contractor removed obstacles in the Southwest Pass, which was restricting deep draft navigation.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] The Louis Armstrong New Orleans International Airport reopened on Monday, September 12, 2005, to cargo traffic, with limited passenger service expected to resume Tuesday, September 13, 2005.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] Officials awarded a $30.9 million contract to repair the, "twin spans" I-10 bridge to New Orleans to Boh Brothers Construction Co. on September 12, 2005.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] It was estimated that 45 days would be required before the bridge could reopen to normal traffic.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] Water pressure had now been restored in the majority of the Jefferson Parish.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] A "boil water" order was still in force on the East Bank, but had been lifted for the West Bank.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] On the East Bank, 17% of sewage pumps were operational, and 39% were operational on the West Bank.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] The Mississippi River Gulf Outlet was closed to deep draft vessels.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] The inland portion was serving as an alternative route to the GIWW due to closure of the IHNC for shallow draft vessels.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] Preliminary surveys indicated a controlling depth of 27'.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] The Army Corps subsequently recommended closing the outlet permanently.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] By September 21, 2005, the Army Corps of Engineers had begun closing two damaged canals at noon in preparation for storm surges associated with Hurricane Rita.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] The 17th Street and London Avenue Canals were closed with steel sheet piling by evening and remained closed until the threat of severe weather passed.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] Steel sheets would be driven deep into the canal beds near Lake Pontchartrain, providing protection from possible storm surges from the lake rushing into the damaged canals.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] By September 23, 2005, although high water caused by Hurricane Rita flowed over the temporary closure on the Industrial Harbor Navigation canal, the structure remained intact.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] This reflooded the already-devastated Lower Ninth Ward and also the Gentilly neighborhood to the west.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] The Delta Works are a series of constructions built between 1953 and 1997 in the southwest of the Netherlands to protect a large area of land around the Rhine-Meuse-Scheldt delta from the sea.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] The works consist of dams, sluices, locks, levees, and storm surge barriers.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] The works were initiated after the North Sea flood of 1953 in which 2,170 people were killed.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] Some people, including Speaker of the House Dennis Hastert, questioned whether federal funds should pay to rebuild New Orleans.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] Others consider New Orleans's unique cultural heritage and history to be as important to the United States as, for instance, Venice is to Italy; they maintain that to not rebuild and reoccupy the city would be an immeasurable loss in that regard.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] The *Times-Picayune* ran a front-page editorial arguing for national help.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] It has been argued that since the US Army Corps of Engineers has had oversight over the levee system since the Great Mississippi Flood of 1927 and most of the destruction in the city occurred due to the levee failure, the federal government should be responsible for rebuilding.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] Senator Mary Landrieu said that Louisiana's offshore petroleum leases generate billions of dollars in revenues for the federal government's general fund, more than would be needed to restore wetlands and upgrade levee/flood control for South Louisiana to withstand category 5 storms.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] She argued that the federal government should either earmark some of that income for such projects or allow Louisiana to keep a significant portion of that revenue so the state could take care of its needs itself.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] The Louisiana Recovery Authority (LRA) was a governmental body created after Katrina by Governor Kathleen Blanco to plan for the recovery and rebuilding of Louisiana under the leadership of the founding executive director, Andy Kopplin.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] The LRA designed and ran the Road Home program which was funded by the U.S.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] Government to help Louisiana residents rebuild or sell their severely damaged houses.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] Complaints started as soon as the state launched the massive program.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] Community leaders said the largest rebuilding program in the U.S. would be unfair to the state's poorest residents.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] Louisiana homeowners reported that losing all their homes was less painful than dealing with the reconstruction process in their state.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] Since Katrina, the US Army Corps of Engineers has made a $14.45 billion investment in the area around New Orleans and provided 100% of the cost.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] In May 2022, nearly 17 years after Katrina, John Bel Edwards, then governor of Louisiana, declared all projects to repair and improve the New Orleans flood prevention system complete, at an estimated final cost of $15.6 billion.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] In September 2005, a class action lawsuit was filed against the United States Army Corps of Engineers, the federal agency tasked in the Flood Control Act of 1965 to design and build the protective levees and floodwalls for New Orleans.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] Duval, Jr, dismissed the case on February 1, 2008 stating that while the Army Corps was responsible for the design and construction errors in the flood protection, it could not be held financially liable due to provisions in the Flood Control Act of 1928 which holds the Army Corps immune.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] On August 2, 2007, a judge ruled that some insurance companies were not liable for the damages sustained during Katrina.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] The Greater New Orleans Urban Water Plan (UWP) is a collaborative, multibillion dollar post-Katrina redevelopment plan for the New Orleans metropolitan area.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] Originally released in 2013, the UWP is the result of collaborative efforts among Greater New Orleans, Inc., local civic leaders, and stormwater management experts.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] Waggonner & Ball Architects, a private firm based in New Orleans, coordinated the project with the support of Greater New Orleans, Inc.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] The project sought to rethink New Orleans's stormwater management and drainage infrastructure to ensure the city's longevity amidst subsidence and climate change concerns.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] Additionally, a major component of the project was the revitalization and economic development of areas within the city that had been severely impacted by the hurricane.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] In November 2013, Waggonner & Ball produced the UWP in three parts: Vision, Urban Design, and Implementation.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] Waggonner & Ball coined the term "living with water" to describe the UWP's emphasis on storing and holding water within the city limits rather than pumping water out into major waterways, such as the Mississippi River and Lake Pontchartrain.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] The project views water as an asset and draws upon the Dutch model for flood control in the Netherlands.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] The plan relies on green infrastructure practices, such as bioswales, greenways, blueways, rain gardens, and permeable pavement, to capture and store excess stormwater.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] The project is divided among the Jefferson–Orleans basin, the Orleans East Basin, and the St.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] Bernard Basin, and is a coordinated effort among Jefferson, Orleans, and St.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] Waggonner & Ball estimates that fully implementing the UWP would cost $6.2 billion with long-term projected benefits of $22 billion, whereas maintaining the pre-Katrina infrastructure model would cost New Orleans more than $10 billion over the next few decades.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] The project has served as a primary guide for the New Orleans City Council's Capital Improvement Plan since the adoption of the 2020–2024 Capital Improvement Plan in September 2019 under Mayor LaToya Cantrell.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] Bars were the first businesses to reopen in many areas; two remained open in the French Quarter even during the worst of the storm and the official mandatory evacuation.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] Most other businesses, such as gas stations, appliance stores, and supermarkets, followed somewhat later as they required more work before they could reopen.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] Three months after the storm, most open restaurants were serving food and drink in disposable plates and cups because of the shortage of dishwashers.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] Despite many restaurants offering wages double pre-Katrina levels for dishwashers, there were few takers as untrained laborers were able to make more money in demolition- and reconstruction-related industries.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] Ten months later, things had improved, though there were still labor shortages in many service industries.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] Some of the few businesses to do significantly better business after Katrina than before were new car dealers.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] Flooding totaled an estimated 200,000 vehicles in Metro New Orleans, and dealers able to get in shipments of new cars quickly found customers.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] After local reporters found a used car dealer selling partially cleaned up flooded cars with restored engines but still soggy trunks, the state legislature quickly passed legislation mandating that cars declared totaled must be dismantled, crushed, or otherwise disposed of and could not be resold.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] The American Library Association held its annual convention in New Orleans in June 2006; the estimated 18,000 attendees represented the first citywide convention in New Orleans since Hurricane Katrina.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] The National Association of Realtors also held their annual convention in New Orleans bringing 30,000 attendees to the city in November 2006.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] The HIMSS healthcare information technology convention and the American College of Cardiology convention, both held in the spring of 2007, each had more than 24,000 attendees.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] The Essence Music Festival returned to the Crescent City in July 2007 after being displaced to Houston in 2006.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] Several national travel guides have once again listed New Orleans as one of the top five places to visit in the country.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] The Bayou Classic, the traditional football game between Southern University and Grambling State University, returned in November 2006 after being displaced to Houston for its 2005 game.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] The National Football League made a commitment to the city with the return of the New Orleans Saints, following speculation about a move to San Antonio or Los Angeles.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] The National Basketball Association has made a commitment with the return of the New Orleans Hornets (now the Pelicans), which played in both New Orleans and Oklahoma City, in the 2005–2006 and 2006–2007 seasons, returning fully for the 2007–2008 season.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] (Oklahoma City became a permanent member of the NBA in the 2007–2008 season.) New Orleans was granted the 2008 NBA All Star Game, which usually generates millions of dollars in revenue for the host city.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] Tulane University hosted the first and second rounds of the 2007 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Championship.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] The Hornets were renamed to the Pelicans before the 2013–2014 season, and the former name was reclaimed by the then–Charlotte Bobcats the next season.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p01] In mid-March 2007, a local group of investors began conducting a study to see if the city could support a Major League Soccer team.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] Repopulating the city has been steady but gradual, with neither the rapid return of most evacuees hoped for by some optimists nor the long term "ghost town" desertion of the city feared by some pessimists.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] In early 2006, the RAND Corporation estimated that, even in 2008, the city's population would only be little more than half what it was before the storm hit; however by July 2007 the city's population was estimated at about two-thirds (or close to 300,000 residents) of that before the disaster.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] Flooded-out areas presented more problems.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] The city had no comprehensive plan for what to do about flooded areas.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] Thousands of property owners have been gutting and repairing their property, some in the lowest lying areas of town.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] Contractors and workers from out-of-state and other countries came in great numbers doing demolition and reconstruction work, some filling hotels and rental property, others living in trailers and tent cities set up in city parks and parking lots.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] Sportscaster Mike Tirico incorrectly generalized on *Monday Night Football* in September 2006, some areas, like the Lower Ninth Ward and Gentilly, still looked as badly damaged as the day the storm passed through.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] However, in each of those neighborhoods thousands of truckloads of debris were removed, hundreds of unsalvageable houses demolished, and work on gutting and repairs has been constant since the city has reopened.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] While the evacuation prior to Katrina using contraflow lane reversal was the most successful rapid evacuation of a major city in the history of the United States, too little attention was paid to those with a car, credit cards, road experience and/or family out of town.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] Mainly due to their poverty, these residents lacked the resources to relocate somewhere else, or even the resources to evacuate the city.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] Therefore there was a great inequity in who was able to evacuate the city and who was forced to stay.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] Army Corps of Engineers set up the "Blue Roof Program" of putting blue tarps over damaged roofs.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] The tarps kept out rain until more permanent roof repairs could be made.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] Thousands of blue tarps were seen throughout the city; however, a number of official restrictions meant some residents were unable to benefit from this recovery program.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] Likewise, a number of subcontractors paid by the Corps only did "easy" low-pitch one-story roofs, choosing not to return to do more difficult roofs.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] Some New Orleanians lived for months in homes with sizable holes in their roofs.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] Among the popular handouts at Red Cross relief stations were 5-gallon buckets, many put to use as rain catchers.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] Six months after the storm, many of the hastily placed blue roof tarps were in tatters, leaving those homes vulnerable again.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] Many people did not succeed in getting permanent roof repairs from such reasons as long waiting lists for reliable contractors and waits for insurance payment.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] Seven months after the storm, two-thirds of the requested FEMA trailers (designed for short term emergency housing immediately after a disaster) had been delivered.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] Many of these trailers, however, could not be occupied or, if occupied, were not properly functional.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] Delays of weeks or months in hooking up electricity and water to trailers were common, and mechanical and bureaucratic problems prevented use of the trailers.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] In June 2006, the State of Louisiana finally awarded a contract to DRC, Inc. of Mobile, Alabama to remove thousands of abandoned cars strewn throughout New Orleans after Hurricane Katrina.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] On January 11, 2006, the local newspaper, *The Times-Picayune* ran an article describing a post-disaster map for rebuilding the city, dubbed the Green Dot Map.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] It was proposed by the Urban Planning Committee as part of the Bring New Orleans Back Commission convened by Mayor Ray Nagin to guide reconstruction.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] An earlier version of the map discussed parksin many neighborhoods with improved drainage.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] That version contained green dots drawn with dashed lines and no fill that were intended to be possibilities.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] A second map the one first revealed to the public, was created by the *Times-Picayune* staff.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] The new map condensed several maps into one, and also filled in the dashed green circles to make solid ones.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] Instead of tentative areas for parks and drainage, the new map communicated definite greenspaces that appeared to wipe out entire neighborhoods.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] Additionally, the green dots were in low and middle income neighborhoods, and not in highest income ones.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] The Green Dot Map is regarded as a catalyst for transforming New Orleans from a top-down approach to a bottom-up community-driven approach.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] Residents were authorized to return to examine homes after the storm on Monday, September 5, 2005.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] In downtown New Orleans, several places were indeed producing power.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] Due to contaminated water and uninhabitable conditions, the Mayor ordered that all citizens be evacuated by September 6.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] As lead planners for District 4, the district that includes the "largest concentration of public housing in the city" (Iberville, St.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] Reconstruction has been easiest and quickest in the areas least damaged by the storm, mostly corresponding to the parts of the city developed before about 1900.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] These areas were built on naturally higher ground along the River front (such as Old Carrollton, Uptown, the Old Warehouse District, the French Quarter, Old Marigny, and Bywater), along with areas along natural ridges (such as Esplanade Ridge, Bayou St.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] Most of these older areas had no flooding at all or escaped serious flooding because of the raised design of older architecture which prevented floodwaters from entering homes.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] Another high area, much of which escaped serious flooding, was the set of Lake Shore developments between Lake Pontchartrain and Robert E.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] Lee Boulevard, built at a higher level than nearby land from mid-20th century dredging.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] Due to the direction of the storm and the movement of storm surge, the West Bank section of the city, Algiers was spared flooding and became the first part of the city itself to officially reopen to residents.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] Reconstruction of each section of the area has been addressed in the Army Corps LACPR Final Technical Report which identifies areas to not be rebuilt and areas buildings need to be elevated.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] The Corps of Engineers will submit the report to Congress for consideration, planning, and response in mid-2009.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] After the storm, residents began repopulating the city, and with that came more inequity.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] During this rebuilding period of New Orleans a larger percentage of White residents returned back to the city than did Black residents.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] This was attributed to the fact White neighborhoods, like Lakeview, bounced back a lot faster than most Black neighborhoods, like the Ninth Ward.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] This is in part because of the length of time to get utilities like water and electricity working in these communities; reliance on public transit and public schools; and the lack of flood insurance.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] Furthermore, White people returning to New Orleans at higher rates than Black people was attributed to an unwillingness of planners to rebuild low-income housing.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] In September 2005, the Washington Post noted former 10-term Republican Congressman Richard H.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] Baker from Baton Rouge reportedly told lobbyists, "We finally cleaned up public housing in New Orleans.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] We couldn't do it, but God did", and criticized his lack of concern for the lower income residents.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] FEMA caseworkers were charged with the responsibility of helping evacuees find housing and employment.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] Caseworkers had to help some former residents realize that moving back was unrealistic because some of the city was not being rebuilt.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] This created a diaspora as many evacuees wished to return to New Orleans but were not able to.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] Large areas of the city's public housing were targeted for demolition, inciting vocal protests from some, including architecture critic Nicolai Ouroussoff.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] A challenge facing New Orleans was the exceptionally large homeless population created by Katrina.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] The number of homeless people living in New Orleans doubled to 12,000 people between the hurricane and mid-2007.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] With a post-Katrina population of 300,000 people, this meant that 1 in 25 people were homeless, an extremely high number and nearly three times that of any other US city.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] Most of the homeless were Katrina evacuees who returned to higher rents or who fell through the cracks of the federal system that was to provide temporary housing after the disaster.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] There were also some workers who came from out of state for the post-Katrina rebuilding boom but who subsequently lost their jobs.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] Compounding this problem, the number of beds for the homeless in the city decreased from a count of 2,800 before the storm to 2,000 as of May 2008.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] In January 2009, the New Orleans Legal Assistance Corporation's Homeless Department reevaluated the homelessness rate.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] They found that the post-Katrina homeless population decreased by 64% since the last survey two years prior.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] UNITY of Greater New Orleans reported 1,188 homeless people after their 2018 Point-in-Time count performed in January.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] As of 2018, New Orleans has maintained a "functional zero" in veteran homelessness for three years.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] Going forward, UNITY's efforts are focused on support for chronically homeless people with physical and/or mental disabilities.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] Neighborhood and community-based organizations played a significant role in the reconstruction effort after Katrina.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] Network members shared information and resources identified through the network with their own communities and neighbors.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] Early on, members also used NPN as a way to identify and collectively point out issues and collective priorities to local government officials and agencies and propose possible solutions.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] The network eventually established a newspaper, *The Trumpet*, that was circulated locally to disseminate information, highlight and celebrate progress, and to facilitate connections for collaboration.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] Initially, a total of 63,000 troops added in the relief effort - 18,000 active-duty troops and 45,000 National Guard.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] The American Red Cross made a belated but nonetheless significant entry into the city in mid-September; and by the start of October had a number of relief centers set up around the city.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] These provided hot meals, packaged food, bottled water and other supplies like diapers, mops, and dust masks.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] The Salvation Army also had many stations giving food.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] Temporary free clinics provided some medical care.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] Towards the end of 2005, the relief centers were wound down, starting with those in functioning parts of the city.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] Red Cross meals continued at a much smaller scale into 2006 from trucks traveling around the worst-hit and poorest neighborhoods.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] The Southern Baptist Convention sent feeding units to New Orleans and the Mississippi Gulf Coast the day after Katrina struck New Orleans.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] The volunteer teams helped in the reconstruction efforts in New Orleans and the surrounding parishes.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] First Baptist Church of New Orleans worked hand-in-hand with Habitat for Humanity with the Baptist Crossroads Project, in an effort to rebuild homes in the Upper Ninth Ward.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] Common Ground Collective had two relief centers in the Ninth Ward of New Orleans, providing food, clothing, and a tool library.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] The larger center was in the Upper 9th Ward, with a smaller one in the worst hit part of the Lower 9th Ward.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints began bringing in load after load of food and water for local members and residents to several areas of the city.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] Thousands of church members came in on rotating weekends to help clean up debris, gut houses and cut up fallen trees all over the city.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] In addition to the home repairs, the church full-time counselors were available to provide mental health assistance; and church employment centers—offices that aid with finding jobs—opened their doors to everyone, regardless of religion.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] Habitat for Humanity has been active in building homes at an accelerated pace since the storm.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] Initially, the organization had volunteers gutting homes; but since returned to its primary mission of fighting poverty housing.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] Catholic Charities also was very active with volunteers repairing damaged houses and churches throughout the area.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] Camp Hope in Violet, Louisiana housed volunteers in the Hurricane Katrina recovery effort of St.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] In 2005 The foundation held an auction to benefit musicians affected by Hurricane Katrina Thanks to the generosity of the foundation's chairwoman, Ms.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] Agnes Varis, they were able to create employment programs which have made it possible to keep the artists and their music alive in New Orleans.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] Lieutenant Governor Mitch Landrieu (who later became Mayor of New Orleans) declared that Louisiana housed America's soul, and its revival was of paramount importance.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] As New Orleans began reviving its local businesses, the reestablishment of the city's restaurants, particularly mom and pop eateries, received fervent local and national support.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] New Orleans's cuisine has largely maintained its cultural distinctiveness, linking its citizens with the city's creole roots.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] Long before Hurricane Katrina, 'local' food in New Orleans represented a framework for discussing America's racial binary—a paradigm in which the city has generally attempted to resist.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] Thus, even if race prevented a portion of New Orleanians from "[acknowledging] that they do, indeed, share one culture", culture became recognized as "something shared around which the city's residents could rally" during an arduous rebuild.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] By emphasizing the restoration of not only New Orleans's economic but also its cultural capital, the city yielded the additional benefit of a reinvigorated social capital.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] Nation of Islam leader Louis Farrakhan among other public figures claimed the levees were dynamited to divert waters away from wealthy white areas.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] The conspiracy theory reached a United States House of Representatives committee investigating Katrina when a New Orleans community activist made the claim.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] According to the *New Orleans Times Picayune* this is an "urban myth".
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] Reasons for belief in these theories have been ascribed to the decision by city officials during the Great Mississippi Flood of 1927 to set off 30 tons of dynamite on the levee at Caernarvon, Louisiana which eased pressure on levees at New Orleans but flooded St.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/2005-levee-failures-in-greater-new-orleans-p02] Bernard Parish, the Ninth Ward taking the brunt of the city's flooding during Hurricane Betsy, the general disenfranchisement of blacks and lower-class people, and the similarity of the sound of the levees collapsing to that of a bombing.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] 218 West 57th Street is four stories tall, with a basement, though the top two stories only cover a portion of the site.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] The facade is made largely of white glazed brick with ornamentation made of elaborately carved Indiana Limestone.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] The second story contains an elliptical ogee arch with a tripartite window, while the top of the building has a cornice with modillions.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] The interior originally contained a lounge, reading room, auditorium, offices, and stacks for the ASCE's library.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] When the ASCE moved out, the interior was converted to commercial space, and escalators and elevators were installed.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] The building was proposed in early 1895 to replace the ASCE's previous overcrowded headquarters, and Eidlitz was selected as the architect as a result of an architectural design competition.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] The building opened on November 24, 1897, and an annex was built between 1905 and 1906 to accommodate the ASCE's increased attendance.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] After moving out, the ASCE continued to own 218 West 57th Street until 1966, leasing the space to automotive showrooms and various office tenants.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] The building also housed a Schrafft's restaurant between 1928 and the 1970s, and Lee's Art Shop between 1975 and 2016.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] The New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission designated the building as a city landmark in 2008.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] 218 West 57th Street is on the southern side of 57th Street, between Broadway and Seventh Avenue two blocks south of Central Park, in the Midtown Manhattan neighborhood of New York City.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] The site covers approximately 8,400 square feet (780 m2).
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] It is 75 feet (23 m) wide, with a depth ranging from 107 feet (33 m) on the eastern side to 118 feet (36 m) on the western side.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] The building carries the alternate addresses 218–222 West 57th Street.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] 218 West 57th Street abuts 224 West 57th Street to the west, and a public plaza and 888 Seventh Avenue to the east.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] Other nearby buildings include the Central Park Tower to the northwest, the American Fine Arts Society (also known as the Art Students League of New York building) to the north, the Osborne Apartments to the northeast, the Rodin Studios to the east, and 1740 Broadway to the south.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] 218 West 57th Street is part of a former artistic hub around a two-block section of West 57th Street between Sixth Avenue and Broadway.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] The hub had been developed during the late 19th and early 20th centuries, following the opening of Carnegie Hall at Seventh Avenue in 1891.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] The area contained several headquarters of organizations such as the American Fine Arts Society, the Lotos Club, and the ASCE Society House.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] By the 21st century, the artistic hub had largely been replaced with Billionaires' Row, a series of luxury skyscrapers around the southern end of Central Park.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] Furthermore, in the 20th century, the area was part of Manhattan's "Automobile Row", a stretch of Broadway extending mainly between Times Square at 42nd Street and Sherman Square at 72nd Street.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] In the late 1900s and early 1910s, several large automobile showrooms, stores, and garages were built nearby, including the U.S.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] Rubber Company Building at 1790 Broadway, the B.F.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] Goodrich showroom at 1780 Broadway, and the A.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] Demarest and Peerless Motor Company showrooms at 224 West 57th Street.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] The original building, constructed from 1896 to 1897, was designed by Cyrus L.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] Eidlitz in the French Renaissance Revival style, as the headquarters of the American Society of Civil Engineers (ASCE).
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] The annex, built from 1905 to 1906, was designed by Eidlitz and Andrew C.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] The original structure was constructed by Charles T.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] Wills, and the annex was built by William L.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] The design was meant to complement the American Fine Arts Society and Carnegie Hall.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] The front of the building is at the north, near the main entrance on 57th Street, while the rear of the building is at the south.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] The building contains four stories and a basement, although the third and fourth stories are smaller and only occupy the front portion of the lot.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] The main elevation, or side, of the building faces north toward 57th Street.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] The facade of the ground story is made of Indiana Limestone, while that of the upper floors is made mostly of white brick, with some limestone decoration.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] As viewed from 57th Street, the three vertical bays on the left, or eastern side, are part of the original building.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] The two bays on the right, or western, side are part of the annex.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] The central bay of the original building, the second-easternmost in the current design, is wider than the other bays.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] The facades of the original building and annex have vertical quoins at their edges.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] In the original design, the central entrance on the first floor contained a stoop, with two-part windows on either side.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] The annex also originally had a pair of windows at ground level.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] The first floor was clad in stone during a 1918 renovation, and the original windows were placed with large display windows.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] On the second floor, in the central bay of the original building, is a canopied ogee arch with a tripartite window and ornamental reliefs in the tympanum.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] The other second-story windows have rectangular windows, which are topped by lintels shaped like ogee arches.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] On the third story, the original central bay contains a tripartite window, while the other windows have rectangular windows with small sills and decorative lintels.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] In the original design, a molded band course made of stone stretched horizontally between the third and fourth stories.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] The rectangular fourth-story windows were enlarged in 1939 so that they extended downward into the band course.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] There is a modillioned stone cornice above the fourth floor.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] The eastern wall, made of brick, is visible from the plaza to the east.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] A sign advertising Lee's Art Shop, a former tenant, is painted on the eastern wall.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] It was built with a superstructure made of steel girders and timber.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] When used by the ASCE, the basement had a heating and electrical plant that projected 30 feet (9.1 m) underneath the sidewalk, as well as storage and publication rooms and a janitors' apartment.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] The first floor had a reception room and coat room to the left of the main entrance; a secretary's office to the right; and a lounge in the rear, occupying the entire width of the building and accessed by the main hallway.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] A main staircase led to the second floor, which had a reading room at the front and an auditorium in the rear.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] There were executive and editorial offices on the third floor.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] The stacks for the ASCE's library, on the fourth floor, could hold more than 100,000 volumes.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] Because the upper two floors were not likely to be heavily used, the original design did not include an elevator, but there was a book lift between the second and fourth floors.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] Electricity was provided by two 25-horsepower (19 kW) gas engines.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] The lounge's and auditorium's areas were expanded by 50% in the 1905–1906 construction of the annex.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] In addition, a staircase was built between the lounge and auditorium.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] After the ASCE moved out, the building was used mostly as commercial and office space.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] A brass and iron staircase was added for the Schrafft's restaurant in the building in 1928, and the former auditorium was converted into storage space.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] In addition, a marble-clad elevator was added to the second floor.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] The Schrafft's restaurant took up the first and second floors and could fit 500 guests.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] When Lee's Art Shop renovated the building in 2002, escalators were added between the first, second, and third floors, and an elevator and staircase were built from the first to the fourth floors.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] Many of the original interior designs had been preserved or recreated by Lee's Art Shop.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] The ASCE was founded in 1852 and held its first meetings at the Croton Aqueduct Department building in City Hall Park, Manhattan.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] The meetings occurred regularly through 1855 when the society suspended its activities until 1867.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] The reconvened ASCE met at the Chamber of Commerce of the State of New York until 1875 when the society moved to 4 East 23rd Street.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] The ASCE moved again in 1877 to 104 East 20th Street and in 1881 to 127 East 23rd Street.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] By the 1890s, the ASCE's headquarters on 127 East 23rd Street were becoming overcrowded.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] A historian for the society wrote that many regular meetings were standing-room only, while its annual conventions had to be held in a church because the headquarters were insufficient.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] In May 1895, the ASCE sent a circular to all members concerning the need for a new Society House.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] At the society's annual convention the following month, the ASCE's members responded overwhelmingly in favor of a new Society House, and the matter was forwarded to ASCE's Board of Direction.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] By October 1895, the board had selected a site at 218–220 West 57th Street.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] The site was near the established arts hub on 57th Street and was well-served by public transit, and the eastern border of the site faced what was then the Central Presbyterian Church.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] The ASCE acquired the site in January 1896 for $80,000.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] Immediately afterward, the society convened a committee to oversee the design, contract procurement, and construction of its new Society House.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] Just and contained seven other members, including William Rich Hutton.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] The original plans, to cost $90,000, were prepared by ASCE vice president Joseph M.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] Wilson and called for reception and meeting rooms on the first floor, offices on the second, and the ASCE's library on the third floor.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] The total cost of the project was $45,000 greater than the cost advertised on the circular, so the ASCE started soliciting for subscriptions to fund the building.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] By March, the ASCE board instead decided to host an architectural design competition in which ASCE members and a few "specially invited" architects could participate.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] Twelve plans were submitted, and the committee picked Eidlitz's design in May 1896.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] Excavation at the Society House's site started on July 9, 1896, and cost $4,500.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] At the time, *The New York Times* reported that the building would be made of brick and granite, with terracotta detail.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] Due to uncertainties over funding, the ASCE building committee delayed the awarding of construction contracts until a new president was elected in late 1896.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] By November, the Mutual Life Insurance Company of New York agreed to fund the project, giving the society a $135,000 mortgage.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] The next month, the ASCE's new president Thomas Curtis Clarke announced that a construction contract had been awarded to Charles T.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] The Society House was supposed to have been completed by September 1897, but construction was further held up by strikes among the plasterers and steamfitters working on the project.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] The ASCE Society House officially opened on November 24, 1897, and ultimately cost $206,284 (equivalent to $6,671,267 in 2024).
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] Harrod, ASCE's president, stated that the building had been designed as a headquarters of a professional association rather than as a clubhouse.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] The ASCE stated in a pamphlet that the Society House was the first building in the United States to be built "solely for the use of a professional engineering society".
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] The committee in charge of overseeing the society house's construction was disbanded in late 1898, their work having been completed.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] In 1903, Andrew Carnegie offered to donate $1 million for the construction of the new Engineering Societies' Building on 39th Street.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] The ASCE and several other engineering societies were invited to participate in construction.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] However, the ASCE's members voted against joining the Engineering Societies' Building in March 1904.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] Instead, the board decided to purchase an additional lot to the west of the existing ASCE Society House, measuring about 25 by 115 feet (7.6 by 35.1 m).
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] Plans for the annex were filed in May, and the next month, the ASCE purchased the additional lot from the Island Realty Company for over $100,000.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] That December, the ASCE created a committee to oversee the construction of an annex.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] The work cost approximately $61,000 and was substantially completed at the time of the ASCE's annual meeting in January 1906.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] After the owners of the Engineering Societies' Building paid off the debt on that structure in 1914, they again invited the ASCE to move there.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] If the ASCE agreed, it would be designated a "founding society" of the Engineering Societies' Building.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] The ASCE acquiesced and moved its headquarters to the Engineering Societies' Building by December 1917, after two additional stories were erected for the society there.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] The ASCE continued to own 218 West 57th Street, leasing the building at great profit.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] After the ASCE's relocation, the Federal Food Board immediately leased the space, moving to 218 West 57th Street in December 1917.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] Another tenant, the National Agricultural Prize Commission, had offices in the building between 1917 and 1918.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] The Ajax Rubber Company, at the time one of the largest pneumatic tire makers in the United States, leased 218 West 57th Street in July 1918.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] Brunner modified the ground floor into Ajax's tire showrooms, and the renovation was completed by January 1919.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] The building thus came to be one of several automotive and tire showrooms on Automobile Row.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] Cohen leased the underlying from the ASCE in 1926, intending to replace the old Society House with a skyscraper, though the plans did not come to fruition.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] A Stearns-Knight and Willys-Knight vehicle showroom was opened on the ground floor in July 1927.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] Willys, manufacturer of Stearns-Knight and Willys-Knight vehicles, subleased the salesroom from Ajax the next month.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] The Stearns-Knight salesroom only operated for one year.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] Ajax subsidiary Racine Rubber Company, as well as the Stearns-Knight Sales Corporation, remained in the building through at least 1935.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] Shattuck and Company leased the entire building in March 1928.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] Twelve months later, the company opened its 500-seat Schrafft's restaurant on the first and second floors of the building.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] The restaurant was near both Carnegie Hall and Manhattan's Theater District, operating more than sixteen hours a day.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] It included a second-story grill catering exclusively to men, as well as spaces that could be rented for events.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] The New York State Federation of Women's Clubs moved its headquarters to the building's fourth floor in May 1932.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] After Prohibition in the United States was repealed in 1933, Shattuck requested a liquor license for the 57th Street restaurant the next year.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] The bar, known as the Columbus Room, opened in 1936.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] The third and fourth stories were converted to apartments by 1939, and Bloch & Hesse renovated the restaurant's interior the next year.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] The Federation of Women's Clubs headquarters, as well as the Schrafft's restaurant, hosted a variety of dinners and fundraising events during the 1930s through the 1950s.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] The building was also leased to other tenants, such as a travel agency that occupied the building from 1940 to 1970, as well as winemakers Fromm & Sichel from 1946 to 1956.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] The ASCE finally sold its old Society House in May 1966 for $850,000, to a syndicate headed by George M.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] Two years later, the Arlen Realty and Development Corporation acquired 218 West 57th Street from Horn for about $1 million, and also purchased several adjacent plots to the east.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] The adjacent plots were used for the development of a 628-foot (191 m) skyscraper on 888 Seventh Avenue, which was completed in 1971.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] Arlen preserved 218 West 57th Street, and built a privately owned public plaza separating the old Society House from the new skyscraper, to receive a zoning credit that allowed the skyscraper's maximum height to be increased.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] Meanwhile, Schrafft's was experiencing a financial downturn by 1972, when it sold off several buildings and moved its accounting offices to 218 West 57th Street.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] Xenia Clubs International subleased 13,000 square feet (1,200 m2) in the building the next year for its executive offices.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] Lee's Art Shop rented space at 218 West 57th Street in 1975.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] The family-owned store, founded by Gilbert and Ruth Steinberg in 1951, had previously been located across the street in the Osborne.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] The move had been necessitated because Lee's needed ten times the space of its previous location, which required an open-plan layout for the store.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] The relocation included the renovation of the barrel-vaulted space and the installation of full-height display windows.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] Lee's initially occupied only the first floor, while the upper floors remained in use as offices.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] The upper floors were leased to tenants such as the state's Department of Mental Hygiene and the Restaurant League of New York, as well as public-relations firms, construction contractors, and companies selling typewriter and geriatric equipment.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] The Steinbergs bought 218 West 57th Street from Arlen Realty in 1994 or 1995.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] By 2000, Lee's Art Shop was restoring the building's original features.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] IBEX Construction conducted the renovation, which cost $8 million.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] After the project was completed in 2002, the store's area was expanded from 7,500 to 40,000 square feet (700 to 3,720 m2), and it occupied all four floors of 218 West 57th Street.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] The Steinbergs' furniture and lighting business, in a nearby building, also moved to 218 West 57th Street's upper floors.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] Following Gilbert and Ruth Steinberg's deaths in 2008, ownership of the building passed to their children David Steinberg and Jill Isaacs, who continued to operate Lee's Art Shop.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] The New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission designated 218 West 57th Street as an official city landmark on December 18, 2008.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] Besen & Associates, brokers, had first inquired about the Steinbergs' willingness to sell the store in 2005, to which the family declined.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] However, the Steinberg children were more willing to sell the store after they took over operations of the shop.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] In May 2013, Joseph Safdieh signed a contract to buy 218 West 57th Street from Steinberg and Isaacs for $65 million.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] Two months later, Safdieh sued Steinberg and Isaacs for $10 million over a breach of a sale agreement, and alleged that the store was illegally using the upper stories because they were zoned for office use.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] The lawsuit was subsequently dismissed, and in 2014, Thor Equities and General Growth Properties (GGP) went into contract to the building for $85 million.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] This prompted Safdieh to sue Thor and GGP for allegedly conspiring against him in the sale, though the claims against Thor were subsequently dropped.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] Steinberg and Isaacs, in their contract with Thor and GGP, had requested two and a half years to wind down their operations, and Lee's Art Shop ultimately closed in mid-2016.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] Thor and GGP finalized the building's purchase, along with 126,000 square feet (11,700 m2) of air rights around and above the property, in June 2016.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] Thor and GGP planned to renovate the interior into luxury retail space for $20 million.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] To maximize retail income at 218 West 57th Street, the new owners opted to wait until after 2019, when the Nordstrom store in the neighboring Central Park Tower was set to open.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] During late 2017 and early 2018, the vacant building was used for an interactive exhibit themed to the TV series *Downton Abbey*.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] The next year, 218 West 57th Street was rethemed to the film *Trolls* and the accompanying web television series *Trolls: The Beat Goes On!*, for one year.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] In April 2025, it was announced that an immersive show named *Masquerade*, based on the Broadway musical *The Phantom of the Opera*, would open in the Lee's Art Shop space.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] *Masquerade* was originally supposed to open at 218 West 57th Street on July 31 and run for six weeks, but its run was later extended several times to March 2026.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] The *Real Estate Record and Guide*, in an 1897 piece criticizing various works of architecture on West 57th Street, lauded the building for complementing the American Fine Arts Society.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] The *Iron Age* and the *Times* both praised the building's "richly carved" Indiana limestone facade.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] The *Iron Age* described the building as a "notable addition to the ever increasing list of New York's handsome buildings".
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/220-west-57th-street] Architectural critic Christopher Gray wrote in 2001 that "the light, sophisticated front of the building fit right in with the artistic ambience of West 57th" when it was completed.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/501-c-3] A **501(c)(3) organization** is a United States corporation, trust, unincorporated association, or other type of organization exempt from federal income tax under section 501(c)(3) of Title 26 of the United States Code.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/501-c-3] It is one of the 29 types of 501(c) nonprofit organizations in the U.S.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/501-c-3] The 501(c)(3) exemption applies also for any non-incorporated community chest, fund, cooperating association or foundation organized and operated exclusively for those purposes.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/501-c-3] There are also supporting organizations—often referred to in shorthand form as *Friends of* organizations.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/501-c-3] 26 U.S.C. § 170 provides a deduction for federal income tax purposes, for some donors who make charitable contributions to most types of 501(c)(3) organizations, among others.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/501-c-3] Regulations specify which such deductions must be verifiable to be allowed (e.g., receipts for donations of $250 or more).
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/501-c-3] The basic requirement of obtaining tax-exempt status is that the organization is specifically limited in powers to purposes that the IRS classifies as tax-exempt purposes.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/501-c-3] This limiting of the powers is crucial to obtaining tax exempt status with the IRS and then on the state level.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/501-c-3] Organizations acquire 501(c)(3) tax exemption by filing IRS Form 1023.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/501-c-3] As of 2006, the form must be accompanied by an $850 filing fee if the yearly gross receipts for the organization are expected to average $10,000 or more.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/501-c-3] If yearly gross receipts are expected to average less than $10,000, the filing fee is reduced to $400.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/501-c-3] The IRS released a software tool called Cyber Assistant in 2013, which was succeeded by Form 1023-EZ in 2014.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/501-c-3] There is an alternative way for an organization to obtain status if an organization has applied for a determination and either there is an actual controversy regarding a determination or the Internal Revenue Service has failed to make a determination.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/501-c-3] Prior to December 30, 1969, nonprofit organizations could declare themselves to be tax-exempt under Section 501(c)(3) without first obtaining Internal Revenue Service recognition by filing Form 1023 and receiving a determination letter.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/501-c-3] A nonprofit organization that did so prior to that date could still be subject to challenge of its status by the Internal Revenue Service.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/501-c-3] An individual may not take a tax deduction on gifts made to a 501(c)(3) organization that is organized and operated exclusively for the testing for public safety.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/501-c-3] In the case of tuition fees paid to a private 501(c)(3) school or a church school, the payments are not tax-deductible charitable contributions because they are payments for services rendered to the payee or the payee's children.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/501-c-3] The payments are not tax-deductible charitable contributions even if a significant portion of a church school's curriculum is religious education.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/501-c-3] For a payment to be a tax-deductible charitable contribution, it must be a voluntary transfer of money or other property with no expectation of procuring financial benefit equal to the transfer amount.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/501-c-3] Before donating to a 501(c)(3) organization, a donor can consult the searchable online IRS list of charitable organizations to verify that the organization qualifies to receive tax-deductible charitable contributions.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/501-c-3] Consumers may file IRS Form 13909, with documentation, to complain about inappropriate or fraudulent (i.e., fundraising, political campaigning, lobbying) activities by any 501(c)(3) organization.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/501-c-3] Most 501(c)(3) must disclose the names and addresses of certain large donors to the Internal Revenue Service on their annual returns, but this information is not required to be made available to the public, unless the organization is an independent foundation.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/501-c-3] Churches are generally exempt from this reporting requirement.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/501-c-3] Every 501(c)(3) organization must make available for public inspection its application for tax-exemption, including its Form 1023 or Form 1023-EZ and any attachments, supporting documents, and follow-up correspondence with the Internal Revenue Service.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/501-c-3] Annual returns must be publicly available for a three-year period beginning with the due date of the return, including any extension of time for filing.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/501-c-3] The Internal Revenue Service provides information about specific 501(c)(3) organizations through its Tax Exempt Organization Search online.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/501-c-3] A private nonprofit organization, GuideStar, provides information on 501(c)(3) organizations.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/501-c-3] ProPublica's Nonprofit Explorer provides copies of each organization's Form 990 and, for some organizations, audited financial statements.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/501-c-3] WikiCharities, is a nonprofit database of nonprofits and charities by name, location, and topic, that allows each organization to report its financials, leadership, contacts, and other activities.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/501-c-3] However, Open990 was a searchable database of information about organizations that had to shut down due to IRS delays in posting information online.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/501-c-3] Section 501(c)(3) organizations are prohibited from supporting political candidates, as a result of the Johnson Amendment enacted in 1954.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/501-c-3] Section 501(c)(3) organizations are subject to limits on lobbying, having a choice between two sets of rules establishing an upper bound for their lobbying activities.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/501-c-3] Section 501(c)(3) organizations risk loss of their tax-exempt status if these rules are violated.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/501-c-3] An organization that loses its 501(c)(3) status due to being engaged in political activities cannot subsequently qualify for 501(c)(3) status.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/501-c-3] As a result, it is common for 501(c)(3) organizations to have affiliated nonprofits that are classified as 501(c)(4) organizations, allowing the affiliate to engage in political activity without threatening 501(c)(3) status.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/501-c-3] Churches must meet specific requirements to obtain and maintain tax-exempt status; these are outlined in "IRS Publication 1828: Tax Guide for Churches and Religious Organizations".
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/501-c-3] This guide outlines activities allowed and not allowed by churches under the 501(c)(3) designation.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/501-c-3] Schools for the preparation of its ministers.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/501-c-3] Having an established congregation served by an organized ministry is of central importance.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/501-c-3] Points 4, 6, 8, 11, 12, and 13 are also especially important.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/501-c-3] Nevertheless, the 14-point list is a guideline; it is not intended to be all-encompassing, and other facts and circumstances may be relevant factors.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/501-c-3] Although there is no definitive definition of a church for Internal Revenue Code purposes, in 1986 the United States Tax Court said that "A church is a coherent group of individuals and families that join together to accomplish the religious purposes of mutually held beliefs.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/501-c-3] The United States Tax Court has stated that, while a church can certainly broadcast its religious services by radio, radio broadcasts themselves do not constitute a congregation unless there is a group of people physically attending those religious services.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/501-c-3] A church can conduct worship services in various specific locations rather than in one official location.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/501-c-3] A church may have a significant number of people associate themselves with the church on a regular basis, even if the church does not have a traditional established list of individual members.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/501-c-3] In order to qualify as a tax-exempt church, church activities must be a significant part of the organization's operations.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/501-c-3] An organization whose operations include a substantial nonexempt commercial purposes, such as operating restaurants and grocery stores in a manner consistent with a particular religion's religious beliefs does not qualify as a tax-exempt church.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/501-c-3] In practice, hospital policies often don't cover outside contracted physicians or narrowly defined medically necessary services, leaving patients who technically qualify for charity care still responsible for significant medical bills.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/501-c-3] Organizations described in section 501(c)(3) are prohibited from conducting political campaign activities to intervene in elections to public office.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/501-c-3] Since section 501(c)(3)'s political-activity prohibition was enacted, "commentators and litigants have challenged the provision on numerous constitutional grounds", such as freedom of speech, vagueness, and equal protection and selective prosecution.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/501-c-3] Historically, Supreme Court decisions, such as *Regan v.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/501-c-3] Taxation with Representation of Washington*, suggested that the Court, if it were to squarely examine the political-activity prohibition of § 501(c)(3), would uphold it against a constitutional challenge.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/501-c-3] However, some have suggested that a successful challenge to the political activities prohibition of Section 501(c)(3) might be more plausible in light of *Citizens United v.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/501-c-3] In contrast to the prohibition on political campaign interventions by all section 501(c)(3) organizations, public charities (but not private foundations) may conduct a limited amount of lobbying to influence legislation.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/501-c-3] Although the law states that "no substantial part" of a public charity's activities can go to lobbying, charities with large budgets may lawfully expend a million dollars (under the "expenditure" test) or more (under the "substantial part" test) per year on lobbying.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/501-c-3] The Internal Revenue Service has never defined the term "substantial part" with respect to lobbying.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/501-c-3] To establish a safe harbor for the "substantial part" test, the United States Congress enacted §501(h), called the Conable election after its author, Representative Barber Conable.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/501-c-3] The section establishes limits based on operating budget that a charity can use to determine if it meets the substantial test.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/501-c-3] This changes the prohibition against direct intervention in partisan contests only for lobbying.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/501-c-3] The organization is now presumed in compliance with the substantiality test if they work within the limits.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/501-c-3] The Conable election requires a charity to file a declaration with the IRS and file a functional distribution of funds spreadsheet with their Form 990.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/501-c-3] IRS form 5768 is required to make the Conable election.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/501-c-3] A 501(c)(3) organization is allowed to conduct some or all of its charitable activities outside the United States.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/501-c-3] A 501(c)(3) organization is allowed to award grants to foreign charitable organizations if the grants are intended for charitable purposes and the grant funds are subject to the 501(c)(3) organization's control.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/501-c-3] Additional procedures are required of 501(c)(3) organizations that are private foundations.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/501-c-3] Donors' contributions to a 501(c)(3) organization are tax-deductible only if the contribution is for the use of the 501(c)(3) organization, and that the 501(c)(3) organization is not merely serving as an agent or conduit of a foreign charitable organization.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/501-c-3] The 501(c)(3) organization's management should review the grant application from the foreign organization, decide whether to award the grant based on the intended use of the funds, and require continuous oversight based on the use of funds.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/501-c-3] If the donor imposes a restriction or earmark that the contribution must be used for foreign activities, then the contribution is deemed to be for the foreign organization rather than the 501(c)(3) organization, and the contribution is not tax-deductible.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/501-c-3] The purpose of the grant to the foreign organization cannot include endorsing or opposing political candidates for elected office in any country.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/501-c-3] If a 501(c)(3) organization sets up and controls a foreign subsidiary to facilitate charitable work in a foreign country, then donors' contributions to the 501(c)(3) organization are tax-deductible even if intended to fund the foreign charitable activities.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The **American Society of Civil Engineers** (**ASCE**) is a tax-exempt professional body founded in 1852 to represent members of the civil engineering profession worldwide.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Headquartered in Reston, Virginia, it is the oldest national engineering society in the United States.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Its constitution was based on the older Boston Society of Civil Engineers from 1848.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] ASCE is dedicated to the advancement of the science and profession of civil engineering and the enhancement of human welfare through the activities of society members.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] It has more than 143,000 members in 177 countries.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Its mission is to provide essential value to members, their careers, partners, and the public; facilitate the advancement of technology; encourage and provide the tools for lifelong learning; promote professionalism and the profession; develop and support civil engineers.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The first serious and documented attempts to organize civil engineers as a professional society in the newly created United States were in the early 19th century.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Later, in 1834, an American trade periodical, the "American Railroad Journal," advocated for a similar national organization of civil engineers.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] On December 17, 1838, a petition started circulating asking civil engineers to meet in 1839 in Baltimore, Maryland, to organize a permanent society of civil engineers.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Prior to that, thirteen notable civil engineers largely identifiable as being from New York, Pennsylvania, or Maryland met in Philadelphia.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Forty engineers actually appeared at the February 1839 meeting in Baltimore, including J.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Edgar Thomson (Future Chief Engineer and later President of the Pennsylvania Railroad), Wright, Roberts, Edward Miller, and the Maryland engineers Isaac Trimble and Benjamin Henry Latrobe II and attendees from as far as Massachusetts, Illinois, and Louisiana.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Miller later ascribed the failure to the difficulties of assembling members due to available means for traveling in the country at the time.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] That journal continued discussion on forming an engineers' organization from 1839 thru 1843 serving its own self-interests in advocating its journal as a replacement for a professional society but to no avail.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] During the 1840s, professional organizations continued to develop and organize in the United States.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] During this same period of association incorporations in the 1840s, attempts were again made at organizing an American engineer association.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] They succeeded at first with the Boston Society of Civil Engineers, organized in 1848, and then in October 1852, with an effort to organize a Society of Civil Engineers and Architects in New York.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Craven, Chief Engineer of the Croton Aqueduct and future ASCE president, the meeting resolved to incorporate the society under the name "American Society of Civil Engineers And Architects".
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The founding meeting was held on November 5, 1852, in the offices of the Croton Aqueduct Department at the Rotunda in City Hall Park, Manhattan.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Membership eligibility was restricted to "civil, geological, mining and mechanical Engineers, architects, and other persons who, by profession, are interested in the advancement of science." James Laurie was elected the society's first president.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] At an early meeting of the Board of Direction in 1852, instructions were given for the incorporation of the "American Society of Civil Engineers and Architects" but this was the proper steps were never taken, and therefore this name never legally belonged to the association.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The ASCE held its first meetings at the Croton Aqueduct Department building in City Hall Park.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The meetings only went through 1855 and with the advent of the American Civil War, the society suspended its activities.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The next meeting was more than twelve years later in 1867.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] A number of the original founders, such as James Laurie, J.W.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Talcott, were at this meeting and were dedicated to the objective of resuscitating the society.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] They also planned to put the society on a more permanent footing and elect fifty-four new members.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] With success in that effort, the young engineering society passed a resolution noting that its preservation was mainly due to the persevering efforts of its first president, James Laurie.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The address of President James Pugh Kirkwood delivered at that meeting in 1867 was the first publication of the society, appearing in Volume 1 of *Transactions*, bearing date of 1872.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] On March 4, 1868, by a vote of 17 to 4, the name was changed to "American Society of Civil Engineers", but it was not until April 17, 1877, that the lack of incorporation was discovered and the proper steps taken to remedy the defect.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The society was then chartered and incorporated in New York state.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The ASCE commissioned a new headquarters at 220 West 57th Street in 1895.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The building was completed in 1897 and served as the society's headquarters until 1917 when the ASCE moved to the Engineering Societies' Building.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Nora Stanton Barney was among the first women in the United States to earn a civil engineering degree, graduating from Cornell University in 1905.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] In the same year, she was accepted as a junior member of the organization and began work for the New York City Board of Water Supply.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] She was the first female member of ASCE, where she was allowed to be a junior member, but was denied advancement to associate member in 1916 because of her gender.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] In 2015, she was posthumously advanced to ASCE Fellow status.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] ASCE's headquarters relocated to the Engineering Societies' Building in 1917; additional floors were added on top of the building to accommodate the society's new offices.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The weight of the extra stories could not be supported on the existing pilings, so four new steel columns were constructed through the structure, supported directly on the bedrock.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] In 1961, ASCE's headquarters moved from the Engineering Societies' Building to the United Engineering Center, a new skyscraper built for twenty different engineering societies across from the headquarters of the United Nations.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] In 1996, ASCE relocated its headquarters from New York City to Reston, Virginia.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The relocation to the Washington metropolitan area was made to bring ASCE's headquarters closer to the legislative branch of the federal government and also reduced operating costs.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] In 1999, the ASCE elected the top-ten "civil engineering achievements that had the greatest positive impact on life in the 20th century" in "broad categories".
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Monuments of the Millennium were a "combination of technical engineering achievement, courage and inspiration, and a dramatic influence on the development of [their] communities".
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] ASCE stated that dissemination of technical and professional information to the civil engineering profession was a major goal of the society.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] They also publish an online bibliographic database, conference proceedings, standards, manuals of practice, and technical reports.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The ASCE Library contains 470+ e-books and standards, some with chapter-level access and no restrictive DRM, and 600+ online proceedings.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Each year, more than 55,000 engineers earn continuing education units (CEUs) and/or professional development hours (PDHs) by participating in ASCE's continuing education programs.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] ASCE hosts more than 15 annual and specialty conferences, over 200 continuing education seminars and more than 300 live web seminars.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Meetings include "...committees, task forces, focus groups, workshops and seminars designed to bring together civil engineering experts either from specific fields or those with a broad range of experience and skills.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The engineering programs division directly advances the science of engineering by delivering technical content for ASCE's publications, conferences and continuing education programs.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] It consists of eight discipline-specific institutes, four technical divisions, and six technical councils.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The work is accomplished by over 600 technical committees with editorial responsibility for 28 of ASCE's 33 journals.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] On an annual basis, the division conducts more than twelve congresses and specialty conferences.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] As a founding society of ANSI and accredited standards development organization, ASCE committees use an established and audited process to produce consensus standards under a program supervised by the society's Codes and Standards Committee.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] (CEC), affiliated with ASCE, has been established to support specialty certification academies for civil engineering specialties and is accredited by the Council of Engineering and Scientific Specialty Boards (CESB).
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] CEC also handles safety certification for state, municipal, and federal buildings, formerly the province of the now-defunct Building Security Council.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The Committee on Critical Infrastructure (CCI) provides vision and guidance on ASCE activities related to critical infrastructure resilience, including planning, design, construction, O&M, and event mitigation, response and recovery.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Certification is the recognition of attaining advanced knowledge and skills in a specialty area of civil engineering.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] ASCE offers certifications for engineers who demonstrate advanced knowledge and skills in their area of engineering.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Michel Award for Industry Advancement of Research and the Charles Pankow Award for innovation, 12 scholarships and fellowships for student members.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Created in 1968 by ASCE's Sanitary Engineering Division, the Wesley W.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Horner award is named after former ASCE President Wesley W.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Horner, and given to a recently peer reviewed published paper in the fields of hydrology, urban drainage, or sewerage.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Special consideration is given to private practice engineering work that is recognized as a valuable contribution to the field of environmental engineering.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The Lifetime Achievement Award has been presented annually since 1999 and recognizes five different individual leaders.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] One award is present in each category of design, construction, government, education, and management.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] In July 1946, the Board of Direction authorized annual awards on recommendation by the society's Committee on Research to stimulate research in civil engineering.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Alberta Reed Huber endowed these prizes in honor of her husband, Walter L.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The Huber Prize is considered the highest level mid-career research prize in civil engineering and is awarded for outstanding achievements and contributions in research with respect to all disciplines of civil engineering.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The LTPP International Data Analysis Contest is an annual data analysis contest held by the ASCE in collaboration with the Federal Highway Administration (FHWA).
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The participants utilize Long-Term Pavement Performance Program (LTPP) data as part of their analysis.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] At the instigation of the former students of Nathan Mortimore Newmark, the Nathan M.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Newmark Medal was established in 1975 by the Engineering Mechanics Institute and Structural Engineering Institute of the American Society of Civil Engineers (ASCE) in honor of his contributions in structural engineering and mechanics.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The medal is given to an ASCE member whose outstanding contributions in structural mechanics have substantially strengthened the scientific base of structural engineering, documented in the form of papers or other written presentations.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Nominations are made once a year and due on November 1.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The foundation board of directors has seven persons and its bylaws require that four of the seven directors must be ASCE officers as well and the ASCE executive director and chief financial officer must also be ASCE employees.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The foundation's support is most often to ASCE's charitable, educational and scientific programs.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The foundation's largest program is supporting three strategic areas; lifelong learning and leadership, advocacy for infrastructure investment and the role of civil engineers in sustainable practices.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] In 2014, this foundation's support in these areas was almost US$4 million.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] ASCE provides peer reviews at the request of public agencies and projects as a "means to improve the management and quality of [public agency] services and thus better protect the public health and safety with which they are entrusted".
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] After the 2005 levee failures in Greater New Orleans, the commander of the U.S.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Lawrence Roth, deputy executive director of the ASCE led the ERP development, served as the panel's chief of staff and facilitated its interaction with IPET.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The expert panel's role was to provide an independent technical review of the IPET's activities and findings, as stated at a National Research Council meeting in New Orleans: "an independent review panel ensure[s] that the outcome is a robust, credible and defensible performance evaluation".
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Gen Strock gave all expert review panel members an Outstanding Civilian Service Medals.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] On June 1, 2007, the ASCE issued its expert review panel report, and an accompanying press release.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The corps acknowledged receiving a copy of the letter and refused to comment until the ASCE's Committee on Professional Conduct (CPC) had commented on the complaint.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] It took over a year for the ASCE to announce the results of the CPC.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] On November 14, 2007, ASCE announced that U.S.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] (ret), would lead an independent task force of outside experts to review how ASCE participated in engineering studies of national significance.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] ASCE President David Mongan said the review was to address criticism of ASCE´s role in assisting the Army Corps of Engineers-sponsored investigation of Katrina failures.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Mongan assured citizens of metro New Orleans in a letter to the *Times Picayune*, that ASCE took "this matter very seriously and that appropriate actions are being taken".
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The panel recommended in results released on September 12, 2008, that ASCE should immediately take steps to remove the potential for conflict of interest in its participation in post-disaster engineering studies.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] It concluded that ASCE should draw up an ethics policy to eliminate questions of possible conflicts of interest.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] On April 6, 2009, an internal probe with the ASCE issued a report that ordered a retraction of the ASCE's June 1, 2007, press release.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] On November 5, 2007, New Orleans–based grassroots group *Levees.org* led by Sandy Rosenthal criticized the ASCE's close relationship with the United States Army Corps of Engineers in a spoof online public service announcement.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] On November 12, 2007, the ASCE asked Levees.org to remove the video from the internet, threatening the organization with legal action if it did not comply.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] On November 13, the Times-Picayune posted the video on its website.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] In March 2008, Levees.org announced that records obtained under the Freedom of Information Act revealed that as early October 2005, the Army Corps of Engineers had directed and later paid the ASCE more than $1.1 million for its peer review (Grant Number: W912HZ-06-1-0001).
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The grant also paid for a series of misleading ASCE presentations attempting to shift blame away from the corps and onto local levee officials.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Members of the ASCE are forbidden from making false or exaggerated statements and also from making statements for an interested party unless this is disclosed.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Levees.org claimed the records showed how the external peer review would be done in four phases: Phase 1 was research and analysis on the performance of the levees, floodwalls and other important structures.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Phase 2 was provision of information on the current system to prevent future flooding.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Phase 3 was provision of information to evaluate alternative approaches to flood protection.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] Phase 4 was transfer information and knowledge gained to a broader audience within Corps and its consultancy community to communicate lessons learned.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] The group claimed that these records were proof that ASCE's routine powerpoint presentation from 2007 and 2008 were a public relations campaign to repair the corps' reputation.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/american-society-of-civil-engineers] ASCE officials responded that ASCE paid for the powerpoint presentations itself and had not used USACE grant money for that purpose.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/ansi] The **American National Standards Institute** (**ANSI**) is a private nonprofit organization that oversees the development of voluntary consensus standards for products, services, processes, systems, and personnel in the United States.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/ansi] The organization also coordinates U.S. standards with international standards so that American products can be used worldwide.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/ansi] ANSI accredits standards that are developed by representatives of other standards organizations, government agencies, consumer groups, companies, and others.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/ansi] These standards ensure that the characteristics and performance of products are consistent, that people use the same definitions and terms, and that products are tested the same way.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/ansi] ANSI also accredits standards developing organizations (SDOs) and provides a searchable directory of accredited standards developers (ASDs).
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/ansi] ANSI similarly accredits organizations that carry out product or personnel certification in accordance with requirements defined in international standards.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/ansi] The organization's headquarters are in Washington, D.C.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/ansi] ANSI's operations office is located in New York City.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/ansi] The ANSI annual operating budget is funded by the sale of publications, membership dues and fees, accreditation services, fee-based programs, and international standards programs.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/ansi] Many ANSI regulations are incorporated by reference into United States federal statutes (i.e. by OSHA regulations referring to individual ANSI specifications).
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/ansi] ANSI does not make these standards publicly available, and charges money for access to these documents; it further claims that it is copyright infringement for them to be provided to the public by others free of charge.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/ansi] These assertions have been the subject of criticism and litigation.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/ansi] ANSI was most likely formed in 1918, when five engineering societies and three government agencies founded the **American Engineering Standards Committee** (**AESC**).
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/ansi] In 1928, the AESC became the **American Standards Association** (**ASA**).
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/ansi] In 1966, the ASA was reorganized and became the **United States of America Standards Institute** (**USASI**).
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/ansi] In February 1969, Ralph Nader harshly criticized the USASI in public remarks as "manifestly deceptive" in several different ways.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/ansi] He specifically attacked the name USASI as improperly implying some kind of official connection with the federal government of the United States.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/ansi] had been members of the United Engineering Society (UES).
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/ansi] At the behest of the AIEE, they invited the U.S. government Departments of War, Navy (combined in 1947 to become the Department of Defense or DOD) and Commerce to join in founding a national standards organization.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/ansi] According to Adam Stanton, the first permanent secretary and head of staff in 1919, AESC started as an ambitious program and little else.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/ansi] Staff for the first year consisted of one executive, Clifford B.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/ansi] LePage, who was on loan from a founding member, ASME.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/ansi] An annual budget of $7,500 was provided by the founding bodies.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/ansi] In 1931, the organization (renamed ASA in 1928) became affiliated with the U.S.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/ansi] National Committee of the International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC), which had been formed in 1904 to develop electrical and electronics standards.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/ansi] ANSI's members are government agencies, organizations, academic and international bodies, and individuals.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/ansi] In total, the Institute represents the interests of more than 270,000 companies and organizations and 30 million professionals worldwide.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/ansi] ANSI's market-driven, decentralized approach has been criticized in comparison with more planned and organized international approaches to standardization.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/ansi] Although ANSI itself does not develop standards, the Institute oversees the development and use of standards by accrediting the procedures of standards developing organizations.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/ansi] ANSI accreditation signifies that the procedures used by standards developing organizations meet the institute's requirements for openness, balance, consensus, and due process.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/ansi] ANSI also designates specific standards as American National Standards, or ANS, when the Institute determines that the standards were developed in an environment that is equitable, accessible and responsive to the requirements of various stakeholders.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/ansi] Voluntary consensus standards quicken the market acceptance of products while making clear how to improve the safety of those products for the protection of consumers.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/ansi] There are approximately 9,500 American National Standards that carry the ANSI designation.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/ansi] The institute is the official U.S. representative to the two major international standards organizations, the International Organization for Standardization (ISO), as a founding member, and the International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC), via the U.S.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/ansi] ANSI participates in almost the entire technical program of both the ISO and the IEC, and administers many key committees and subgroups.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/ansi] In many instances, U.S. standards are taken forward to ISO and IEC, through ANSI or the USNC, where they are adopted in whole or in part as international standards.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/ansi] Adoption of ISO and IEC standards as American standards increased from 0.2% in 1986 to 15.5% in May 2012.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/ansi] Each of the panels works to identify, coordinate, and harmonize voluntary standards relevant to these areas.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/ansi] In 2009, ANSI and the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) formed the Nuclear Energy Standards Coordination Collaborative (NESCC).
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/ansi] NESCC is a joint initiative to identify and respond to the current need for standards in the nuclear industry.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/asce-journal-of-structural-engineering] The ***Journal of Structural Engineering*** is the principal professional peer-reviewed journal of the American Society of Civil Engineers, the oldest professional civil engineering society in the United States.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/asce-journal-of-structural-engineering] The journal is one of the flagship journals of the Society.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/asce-journal-of-structural-engineering] It is sponsored by its division, the ASCE Structural Engineering Institute.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/asce-journal-of-structural-engineering] This journal shares knowledge and advances in the field of structural engineering.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/asce-journal-of-structural-engineering] Originally, the journals was part of the *proceedings of the American Society of Civil Engineers,* first published in 1873 The Journal started publishing separately in 1956 as part of the ASCE *Journal of the Structural Division* (ISSN 0044-8001).
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/asce-journal-of-structural-engineering] In 1983, the title was changed to the *Journal of Structural Engineering* (ISSN 0733-9445).
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/asce-journal-of-structural-engineering] The *Journal of Structural Engineering* is indexed in Scopus, Web of Science, and Engineering Index, Civil engineering database, OCLC (WorldCat).
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/asce-journal-of-structural-engineering] It is available on ProQuest and EbscoNet.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/asce-library] ASCE Journals first appeared online in the Fall of 2000.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/asce-library] The online collection was designated ASCE Research Library in the Fall of 2004 with the addition of ASCE Proceedings papers.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/asce-library] In June 2012, the platform migrated from Scitation, to Literatum managed by Atypon and the site was renamed ASCE Library.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/asce-library] In June 2013, e-books and standards were added with the ability to download individual book chapters as well as complete books.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/asce-library] In 2016, ASCE added access to premium content from Civil Engineering Magazine.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/asce-library] The ASCE Library offers online access to more than 150,000 technical and professional papers.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/asce-library] It encompasses the full text of papers published in 35 journals (as of 2019) from 1983 to the present, conference proceedings from 2000 to the present, and full text of ASCE standards and e-books.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/asce-library] The ASCE Library is supplemented by Civil Engineering Database (CEDB), a free bibliographic database offering records of all publications by American Society of Civil Engineers since 1872.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/asce-library] CEDB is updated at the end of each month.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/asce-library] The update includes the journal content for the following month and all other content published in the previous month.
[src:american-society-of-civil-engineers/asce-library] Includes more than 750 proceedings titles and 70,000 technical papers, as well as a complete archive of conference proceedings papers from 2000 to present (selected earlier conference proceedings are also included).
